  76 @add_arg_scope
  77 def avg_pool2d(inputs,
  78                kernel_size,
  79                stride=2,
  80                padding='VALID',
  81                data_format=DATA_FORMAT_NHWC,
  82                outputs_collections=None,
  83                scope=None):
  84   """Adds a 2D average pooling op.
  85 
  86   It is assumed that the pooling is done per image but not in batch or channels.
  87 
  88   Args:
  89     inputs: A 4-D tensor of shape `[batch_size, height, width, channels]` if
  90       `data_format` is `NHWC`, and `[batch_size, channels, height, width]` if
  91       `data_format` is `NCHW`.
  92     kernel_size: A list of length 2: [kernel_height, kernel_width] of the
  93       pooling kernel over which the op is computed. Can be an int if both
  94       values are the same.
  95     stride: A list of length 2: [stride_height, stride_width].
  96       Can be an int if both strides are the same. Note that presently
  97       both strides must have the same value.
  98     padding: The padding method, either 'VALID' or 'SAME'.
  99     data_format: A string. `NHWC` (default) and `NCHW` are supported.
 100     outputs_collections: The collections to which the outputs are added.
 101     scope: Optional scope for name_scope.
 102 
 103   Returns:
 104     A `Tensor` representing the results of the pooling operation.
 105 
 106   Raises:
 107     ValueError: If `data_format` is neither `NHWC` nor `NCHW`.
 108   """
 109   if data_format not in (DATA_FORMAT_NCHW, DATA_FORMAT_NHWC):
 110     raise ValueError('data_format has to be either NCHW or NHWC.')
 111   with ops.name_scope(scope, 'AvgPool2D', [inputs]) as sc:
 112     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
 113     df = ('channels_first'
 114           if data_format and data_format.startswith('NC') else 'channels_last')
 115     layer = pooling_layers.AveragePooling2D(
 116         pool_size=kernel_size,
 117         strides=stride,
 118         padding=padding,
 119         data_format=df,
 120         _scope=sc)
 121     outputs = layer.apply(inputs)
 122     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc, outputs)
 123

 125 @add_arg_scope
 126 def avg_pool3d(inputs,
 127                kernel_size,
 128                stride=2,
 129                padding='VALID',
 130                data_format=DATA_FORMAT_NDHWC,
 131                outputs_collections=None,
 132                scope=None):
 133   """Adds a 3D average pooling op.
 134 
 135   It is assumed that the pooling is done per image but not in batch or channels.
 136 
 137   Args:
 138     inputs: A 5-D tensor of shape `[batch_size, depth, height, width, channels]`
 139       if `data_format` is `NDHWC`, and `[batch_size, channels, depth, height,
 140       width]` if `data_format` is `NCDHW`.
 141     kernel_size: A list of length 3: [kernel_depth, kernel_height, kernel_width]
 142       of the pooling kernel over which the op is computed. Can be an int if both
 143       values are the same.
 144     stride: A list of length 3: [stride_depth, stride_height, stride_width].
 145       Can be an int if both strides are the same. Note that presently
 146       both strides must have the same value.
 147     padding: The padding method, either 'VALID' or 'SAME'.
 148     data_format: A string. `NDHWC` (default) and `NCDHW` are supported.
 149     outputs_collections: The collections to which the outputs are added.
 150     scope: Optional scope for name_scope.
 151 
 152   Returns:
 153     A `Tensor` representing the results of the pooling operation.
 154 
 155   Raises:
 156     ValueError: If `data_format` is neither `NDHWC` nor `NCDHW`.
 157   """
 158   if data_format not in (DATA_FORMAT_NCDHW, DATA_FORMAT_NDHWC):
 159     raise ValueError('data_format has to be either NCDHW or NDHWC.')
 160   with ops.name_scope(scope, 'AvgPool3D', [inputs]) as sc:
 161     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
 162     df = ('channels_first'
 163           if data_format and data_format.startswith('NC') else 'channels_last')
 164     layer = pooling_layers.AveragePooling3D(
 165         pool_size=kernel_size,
 166         strides=stride,
 167         padding=padding,
 168         data_format=df,
 169         _scope=sc)
 170     outputs = layer.apply(inputs)
 171     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc, outputs)

 174 def _fused_batch_norm(inputs,
 175                       decay=0.999,
 176                       center=True,
 177                       scale=False,
 178                       epsilon=0.001,
 179                       activation_fn=None,
 180                       param_initializers=None,
 181                       param_regularizers=None,
 182                       updates_collections=ops.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS,
 183                       is_training=True,
 184                       reuse=None,
 185                       variables_collections=None,
 186                       outputs_collections=None,
 187                       trainable=True,
 188                       data_format=DATA_FORMAT_NHWC,
 189                       zero_debias_moving_mean=False,
 190                       scope=None):
 191   """Adds a Batch Normalization layer from http://arxiv.org/abs/1502.03167.
 192 
 193     "Batch Normalization: Accelerating Deep Network Training by Reducing
 194     Internal Covariate Shift"
 195 
 196     Sergey Ioffe, Christian Szegedy
 197 
 198   Can be used as a normalizer function for conv2d and fully_connected.
 199 
 200   Note: when training, the moving_mean and moving_variance need to be updated.
 201   By default the update ops are placed in `tf.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS`, so they
 202   need to be added as a dependency to the `train_op`. For example:
 203 
 204   ```python
 205     update_ops = tf.get_collection(tf.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS)
 206     with tf.control_dependencies(update_ops):
 207       train_op = optimizer.minimize(loss)
 208   ```
 209 
 210   One can set updates_collections=None to force the updates in place, but that
 211   can have a speed penalty, especially in distributed settings.
 212 
 213   Args:
 214     inputs: A tensor with 2 or more dimensions, where the first dimension has
 215       `batch_size`. The normalization is over all but the last dimension if
 216       `data_format` is `NHWC` and the second dimension if `data_format` is
 217       `NCHW`.
 218     decay: Decay for the moving average. Reasonable values for `decay` are close
 219       to 1.0, typically in the multiple-nines range: 0.999, 0.99, 0.9, etc.
 220       Lower `decay` value (recommend trying `decay`=0.9) if model experiences
 221       reasonably good training performance but poor validation and/or test
 222       performance.
 223     center: If True, add offset of `beta` to normalized tensor.  If False,
 224       `beta` is ignored.
 225     scale: If True, multiply by `gamma`. If False, `gamma` is
 226       not used. When the next layer is linear (also e.g. `nn.relu`), this can be
 227       disabled since the scaling can be done by the next layer.
 228     epsilon: Small float added to variance to avoid dividing by zero.
 229     activation_fn: Activation function, default set to None to skip it and
 230       maintain a linear activation.
 231     param_initializers: Optional initializers for beta, gamma, moving mean and
 232       moving variance.
 233     param_regularizers: Optional regularizer for beta and gamma.
 234     updates_collections: Collections to collect the update ops for computation.
 235       The updates_ops need to be executed with the train_op.
 236       If None, a control dependency would be added to make sure the updates are
 237       computed in place.
 238     is_training: Whether or not the layer is in training mode. In training mode
 239       it would accumulate the statistics of the moments into `moving_mean` and
 240       `moving_variance` using an exponential moving average with the given
 241       `decay`. When it is not in training mode then it would use the values of
 242       the `moving_mean` and the `moving_variance`.
 243     reuse: Whether or not the layer and its variables should be reused. To be
 244       able to reuse the layer scope must be given.
 245     variables_collections: Optional collections for the variables.
 246     outputs_collections: Collections to add the outputs.
 247     trainable: If `True` also add variables to the graph collection
 248       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see `tf.Variable`).
 249     data_format: A string. `NHWC` (default) and `NCHW` are supported.
 250     zero_debias_moving_mean: Use zero_debias for moving_mean.
 251     scope: Optional scope for `variable_scope`.
 252 
 253   Returns:
 254     A `Tensor` representing the output of the operation.
 255 
 256   Raises:
 257     ValueError: If `data_format` is neither `NHWC` nor `NCHW`.
 258     ValueError: If the rank of `inputs` is undefined.
 259     ValueError: If the rank of `inputs` is neither 2 or 4.
 260     ValueError: If rank or `C` dimension of `inputs` is undefined.
 261   """
 262   if data_format not in (DATA_FORMAT_NCHW, DATA_FORMAT_NHWC):
 263     raise ValueError('data_format has to be either NCHW or NHWC.')
 264   with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 265       scope, 'BatchNorm', [inputs], reuse=reuse) as sc:
 266     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
 267     original_shape = inputs.get_shape()
 268     original_inputs = inputs
 269     original_rank = original_shape.ndims
 270     if original_rank is None:
 271       raise ValueError('Inputs %s has undefined rank' % inputs.name)
 272     elif original_rank not in [2, 4]:
 273       raise ValueError('Inputs %s has unsupported rank.'
 274                        ' Expected 2 or 4 but got %d' % (inputs.name,
 275                                                         original_rank))
 276     if original_rank == 2:
 277       channels = inputs.get_shape()[-1].value
 278       if channels is None:
 279         raise ValueError('`C` dimension must be known but is None')
 280       new_shape = [-1, 1, 1, channels]
 281       if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW:
 282         new_shape = [-1, channels, 1, 1]
 283       inputs = array_ops.reshape(inputs, new_shape)
 284     inputs_shape = inputs.get_shape()
 285     if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NHWC:
 286       params_shape = inputs_shape[-1:]
 287     else:
 288       params_shape = inputs_shape[1:2]
 289     if not params_shape.is_fully_defined():
 290       raise ValueError('Inputs %s has undefined `C` dimension %s.' %
 291                        (inputs.name, params_shape))
 292 
 293     # Allocate parameters for the beta and gamma of the normalization.
 294     beta_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(variables_collections,
 295                                                       'beta')
 296     # Float32 required to avoid precision-loss when using fp16 input/output
 297     variable_dtype = dtypes.float32
 298     if not param_initializers:
 299       param_initializers = {}
 300     if not param_regularizers:
 301       param_regularizers = {}
 302     beta_regularizer = param_regularizers.get('beta')
 303     gamma_regularizer = param_regularizers.get('gamma')
 304 
 305     if center:
 306       beta_initializer = param_initializers.get('beta',
 307                                                 init_ops.zeros_initializer())
 308       beta = variables.model_variable(
 309           'beta',
 310           shape=params_shape,
 311           dtype=variable_dtype,
 312           initializer=beta_initializer,
 313           regularizer=beta_regularizer,
 314           collections=beta_collections,
 315           trainable=trainable)
 316     else:
 317       beta = array_ops.constant(0.0, dtype=variable_dtype, shape=params_shape)
 318 
 319     if scale:
 320       gamma_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
 321           variables_collections, 'gamma')
 322       gamma_initializer = param_initializers.get('gamma',
 323                                                  init_ops.ones_initializer())
 324       gamma = variables.model_variable(
 325           'gamma',
 326           shape=params_shape,
 327           dtype=variable_dtype,
 328           initializer=gamma_initializer,
 329           regularizer=gamma_regularizer,
 330           collections=gamma_collections,
 331           trainable=trainable)
 332     else:
 333       gamma = array_ops.constant(1.0, dtype=variable_dtype, shape=params_shape)
 334 
 335     # Create moving_mean and moving_variance variables and add them to the
 336     # appropriate collections. We disable variable partitioning while creating
 337     # them, because assign_moving_average is not yet supported for partitioned
 338     # variables (this needs to be handled carefully, as it may break
 339     # the checkpoint backward compatibility).
 340     with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 341         variable_scope.get_variable_scope()) as local_scope:
 342       local_scope.set_partitioner(None)
 343       moving_mean_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
 344           variables_collections, 'moving_mean')
 345       moving_mean_initializer = param_initializers.get(
 346           'moving_mean', init_ops.zeros_initializer())
 347       moving_mean = variables.model_variable(
 348           'moving_mean',
 349           shape=params_shape,
 350           dtype=variable_dtype,
 351           initializer=moving_mean_initializer,
 352           trainable=False,
 353           collections=moving_mean_collections)
 354       moving_variance_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
 355           variables_collections, 'moving_variance')
 356       moving_variance_initializer = param_initializers.get(
 357           'moving_variance', init_ops.ones_initializer())
 358       moving_variance = variables.model_variable(
 359           'moving_variance',
 360           shape=params_shape,
 361           dtype=variable_dtype,
 362           initializer=moving_variance_initializer,
 363           trainable=False,
 364           collections=moving_variance_collections)
 365 
 366     def _fused_batch_norm_training():
 367       return nn.fused_batch_norm(
 368           inputs, gamma, beta, epsilon=epsilon, data_format=data_format)
 369 
 370     def _fused_batch_norm_inference():
 371       return nn.fused_batch_norm(
 372           inputs,
 373           gamma,
 374           beta,
 375           mean=moving_mean,
 376           variance=moving_variance,
 377           epsilon=epsilon,
 378           is_training=False,
 379           data_format=data_format)
 380 
 381     outputs, mean, variance = utils.smart_cond(
 382         is_training, _fused_batch_norm_training, _fused_batch_norm_inference)
 383 
 384     # If `is_training` doesn't have a constant value, because it is a `Tensor`,
 385     # a `Variable` or `Placeholder` then is_training_value will be None and
 386     # `need_updates` will be true.
 387     is_training_value = utils.constant_value(is_training)
 388     need_updates = is_training_value is None or is_training_value
 389     if need_updates:
 390       if updates_collections is None:
 391         no_updates = lambda: outputs
 392 
 393         def _force_updates():
 394           """Internal function forces updates moving_vars if is_training."""
 395           update_moving_mean = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 396               moving_mean, mean, decay, zero_debias=zero_debias_moving_mean)
 397           update_moving_variance = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 398               moving_variance, variance, decay, zero_debias=False)
 399           with ops.control_dependencies(
 400               [update_moving_mean, update_moving_variance]):
 401             return array_ops.identity(outputs)
 402 
 403         outputs = utils.smart_cond(is_training, _force_updates, no_updates)
 404       else:
 405         moving_vars_fn = lambda: (moving_mean, moving_variance)
 406 
 407         def _delay_updates():
 408           """Internal function that delay updates moving_vars if is_training."""
 409           update_moving_mean = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 410               moving_mean, mean, decay, zero_debias=zero_debias_moving_mean)
 411           update_moving_variance = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 412               moving_variance, variance, decay, zero_debias=False)
 413           return update_moving_mean, update_moving_variance
 414 
 415         update_mean, update_variance = utils.smart_cond(
 416             is_training, _delay_updates, moving_vars_fn)
 417         ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_mean)
 418         ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_variance)
 419 
 420     outputs.set_shape(inputs_shape)
 421     if original_shape.ndims == 2:
 422       outputs = array_ops.reshape(outputs, array_ops.shape(original_inputs))
 423     if activation_fn is not None:
 424       outputs = activation_fn(outputs)
 425     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc.name, outputs)
 426

 428 @add_arg_scope
 429 def batch_norm(inputs,
 430                decay=0.999,
 431                center=True,
 432                scale=False,
 433                epsilon=0.001,
 434                activation_fn=None,
 435                param_initializers=None,
 436                param_regularizers=None,
 437                updates_collections=ops.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS,
 438                is_training=True,
 439                reuse=None,
 440                variables_collections=None,
 441                outputs_collections=None,
 442                trainable=True,
 443                batch_weights=None,
 444                fused=None,
 445                data_format=DATA_FORMAT_NHWC,
 446                zero_debias_moving_mean=False,
 447                scope=None,
 448                renorm=False,
 449                renorm_clipping=None,
 450                renorm_decay=0.99,
 451                adjustment=None):
 452   """Adds a Batch Normalization layer from http://arxiv.org/abs/1502.03167.
 453 
 454     "Batch Normalization: Accelerating Deep Network Training by Reducing
 455     Internal Covariate Shift"
 456 
 457     Sergey Ioffe, Christian Szegedy
 458 
 459   Can be used as a normalizer function for conv2d and fully_connected. The
 460   normalization is over all but the last dimension if `data_format` is `NHWC`
 461   and all but the second dimension if `data_format` is `NCHW`.  In case of a 2D
 462   tensor this corresponds to the batch dimension, while in case of a 4D tensor
 463   this
 464   corresponds to the batch and space dimensions.
 465 
 466   Note: when training, the moving_mean and moving_variance need to be updated.
 467   By default the update ops are placed in `tf.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS`, so they
 468   need to be added as a dependency to the `train_op`. For example:
 469 
 470   ```python
 471     update_ops = tf.get_collection(tf.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS)
 472     with tf.control_dependencies(update_ops):
 473       train_op = optimizer.minimize(loss)
 474   ```
 475 
 476   One can set updates_collections=None to force the updates in place, but that
 477   can have a speed penalty, especially in distributed settings.
 478 
 479   Args:
 480     inputs: A tensor with 2 or more dimensions, where the first dimension has
 481       `batch_size`. The normalization is over all but the last dimension if
 482       `data_format` is `NHWC` and the second dimension if `data_format` is
 483       `NCHW`.
 484     decay: Decay for the moving average. Reasonable values for `decay` are close
 485       to 1.0, typically in the multiple-nines range: 0.999, 0.99, 0.9, etc.
 486       Lower `decay` value (recommend trying `decay`=0.9) if model experiences
 487       reasonably good training performance but poor validation and/or test
 488       performance. Try zero_debias_moving_mean=True for improved stability.
 489     center: If True, add offset of `beta` to normalized tensor. If False, `beta`
 490       is ignored.
 491     scale: If True, multiply by `gamma`. If False, `gamma` is
 492       not used. When the next layer is linear (also e.g. `nn.relu`), this can be
 493       disabled since the scaling can be done by the next layer.
 494     epsilon: Small float added to variance to avoid dividing by zero.
 495     activation_fn: Activation function, default set to None to skip it and
 496       maintain a linear activation.
 497     param_initializers: Optional initializers for beta, gamma, moving mean and
 498       moving variance.
 499     param_regularizers: Optional regularizer for beta and gamma.
 500     updates_collections: Collections to collect the update ops for computation.
 501       The updates_ops need to be executed with the train_op.
 502       If None, a control dependency would be added to make sure the updates are
 503       computed in place.
 504     is_training: Whether or not the layer is in training mode. In training mode
 505       it would accumulate the statistics of the moments into `moving_mean` and
 506       `moving_variance` using an exponential moving average with the given
 507       `decay`. When it is not in training mode then it would use the values of
 508       the `moving_mean` and the `moving_variance`.
 509     reuse: Whether or not the layer and its variables should be reused. To be
 510       able to reuse the layer scope must be given.
 511     variables_collections: Optional collections for the variables.
 512     outputs_collections: Collections to add the outputs.
 513     trainable: If `True` also add variables to the graph collection
 514       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see `tf.Variable`).
 515     batch_weights: An optional tensor of shape `[batch_size]`,
 516       containing a frequency weight for each batch item. If present,
 517       then the batch normalization uses weighted mean and
 518       variance. (This can be used to correct for bias in training
 519       example selection.)
 520     fused: if `None` or `True`, use a faster, fused implementation if possible.
 521       If `False`, use the system recommended implementation.
 522     data_format: A string. `NHWC` (default) and `NCHW` are supported.
 523     zero_debias_moving_mean: Use zero_debias for moving_mean. It creates a new
 524       pair of variables 'moving_mean/biased' and 'moving_mean/local_step'.
 525     scope: Optional scope for `variable_scope`.
 526     renorm: Whether to use Batch Renormalization
 527       (https://arxiv.org/abs/1702.03275). This adds extra variables during
 528       training. The inference is the same for either value of this parameter.
 529     renorm_clipping: A dictionary that may map keys 'rmax', 'rmin', 'dmax' to
 530       scalar `Tensors` used to clip the renorm correction. The correction
 531       `(r, d)` is used as `corrected_value = normalized_value * r + d`, with
 532       `r` clipped to [rmin, rmax], and `d` to [-dmax, dmax]. Missing rmax, rmin,
 533       dmax are set to inf, 0, inf, respectively.
 534     renorm_decay: Momentum used to update the moving means and standard
 535       deviations with renorm. Unlike `momentum`, this affects training
 536       and should be neither too small (which would add noise) nor too large
 537       (which would give stale estimates). Note that `decay` is still applied
 538       to get the means and variances for inference.
 539     adjustment: A function taking the `Tensor` containing the (dynamic) shape of
 540       the input tensor and returning a pair (scale, bias) to apply to the
 541       normalized values (before gamma and beta), only during training. For
 542       example,
 543         `adjustment = lambda shape: (
 544           tf.random_uniform(shape[-1:], 0.93, 1.07),
 545           tf.random_uniform(shape[-1:], -0.1, 0.1))`
 546       will scale the normalized value by up to 7% up or down, then shift the
 547       result by up to 0.1 (with independent scaling and bias for each feature
 548       but shared across all examples), and finally apply gamma and/or beta. If
 549       `None`, no adjustment is applied.
 550 
 551   Returns:
 552     A `Tensor` representing the output of the operation.
 553 
 554   Raises:
 555     ValueError: If `data_format` is neither `NHWC` nor `NCHW`.
 556     ValueError: If the rank of `inputs` is undefined.
 557     ValueError: If rank or channels dimension of `inputs` is undefined.
 558   """
 559   if fused is None:
 560     fused = True
 561 
 562   # Only use _fused_batch_norm if all of the following three
 563   # conditions are true:
 564   # (1) fused is set True;
 565   # (2) it is possible to use (currently it doesn't support batch weights,
 566   #   renorm, and the case when rank is neither 2 nor 4);
 567   # (3) it is used with zero_debias_moving_mean, or an input shape of rank 2,
 568   #   or non-default updates_collections (not implemented in
 569   #   normalization_layers.BatchNormalization yet); otherwise use the fused
 570   #   implementation in normalization_layers.BatchNormalization.
 571   inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
 572   rank = inputs.get_shape().ndims
 573   possible_to_fuse = (
 574       batch_weights is None and not renorm and rank in [2, 4] and
 575       adjustment is None)
 576   if fused and possible_to_fuse and (
 577       zero_debias_moving_mean or rank == 2 or
 578       updates_collections is not ops.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS):
 579     return _fused_batch_norm(
 580         inputs,
 581         decay=decay,
 582         center=center,
 583         scale=scale,
 584         epsilon=epsilon,
 585         activation_fn=activation_fn,
 586         param_initializers=param_initializers,
 587         param_regularizers=param_regularizers,
 588         updates_collections=updates_collections,
 589         is_training=is_training,
 590         reuse=reuse,
 591         variables_collections=variables_collections,
 592         outputs_collections=outputs_collections,
 593         trainable=trainable,
 594         data_format=data_format,
 595         zero_debias_moving_mean=zero_debias_moving_mean,
 596         scope=scope)
 597 
 598   if data_format not in (DATA_FORMAT_NCHW, DATA_FORMAT_NHWC):
 599     raise ValueError('data_format has to be either NCHW or NHWC.')
 600 
 601   layer_variable_getter = _build_variable_getter()
 602   with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 603       scope,
 604       'BatchNorm', [inputs],
 605       reuse=reuse,
 606       custom_getter=layer_variable_getter) as sc:
 607     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
 608 
 609     # Determine whether we can use the core layer class.
 610     if (batch_weights is None and
 611         updates_collections is ops.GraphKeys.UPDATE_OPS and
 612         not zero_debias_moving_mean):
 613       # Use the core layer class.
 614       axis = 1 if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW else -1
 615       if not param_initializers:
 616         param_initializers = {}
 617       beta_initializer = param_initializers.get('beta',
 618                                                 init_ops.zeros_initializer())
 619       gamma_initializer = param_initializers.get('gamma',
 620                                                  init_ops.ones_initializer())
 621       moving_mean_initializer = param_initializers.get(
 622           'moving_mean', init_ops.zeros_initializer())
 623       moving_variance_initializer = param_initializers.get(
 624           'moving_variance', init_ops.ones_initializer())
 625       if not param_regularizers:
 626         param_regularizers = {}
 627       beta_regularizer = param_regularizers.get('beta')
 628       gamma_regularizer = param_regularizers.get('gamma')
 629       layer = normalization_layers.BatchNormalization(
 630           axis=axis,
 631           momentum=decay,
 632           epsilon=epsilon,
 633           center=center,
 634           scale=scale,
 635           beta_initializer=beta_initializer,
 636           gamma_initializer=gamma_initializer,
 637           moving_mean_initializer=moving_mean_initializer,
 638           moving_variance_initializer=moving_variance_initializer,
 639           beta_regularizer=beta_regularizer,
 640           gamma_regularizer=gamma_regularizer,
 641           trainable=trainable,
 642           renorm=renorm,
 643           renorm_clipping=renorm_clipping,
 644           renorm_momentum=renorm_decay,
 645           adjustment=adjustment,
 646           name=sc.name,
 647           _scope=sc,
 648           _reuse=reuse,
 649           fused=fused)
 650       outputs = layer.apply(inputs, training=is_training)
 651 
 652       # Add variables to collections.
 653       _add_variable_to_collections(layer.moving_mean, variables_collections,
 654                                    'moving_mean')
 655       _add_variable_to_collections(layer.moving_variance, variables_collections,
 656                                    'moving_variance')
 657       if layer.beta is not None:
 658         _add_variable_to_collections(layer.beta, variables_collections, 'beta')
 659       if layer.gamma is not None:
 660         _add_variable_to_collections(layer.gamma, variables_collections,
 661                                      'gamma')
 662 
 663       if activation_fn is not None:
 664         outputs = activation_fn(outputs)
 665       return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc.name, outputs)
 666 
 667     # Not supported by layer class: batch_weights argument,
 668     # and custom updates_collections. In that case, use the legacy BN
 669     # implementation.
 670     # Custom updates collections are not supported because the update logic
 671     # is different in this case, in particular w.r.t. "forced updates" and
 672     # update op reuse.
 673     if renorm:
 674       raise ValueError('renorm is not supported with batch_weights, '
 675                        'updates_collections or zero_debias_moving_mean')
 676     inputs_shape = inputs.get_shape()
 677     inputs_rank = inputs_shape.ndims
 678     if inputs_rank is None:
 679       raise ValueError('Inputs %s has undefined rank.' % inputs.name)
 680     dtype = inputs.dtype.base_dtype
 681     if batch_weights is not None:
 682       batch_weights = ops.convert_to_tensor(batch_weights)
 683       inputs_shape[0:1].assert_is_compatible_with(batch_weights.get_shape())
 684       # Reshape batch weight values so they broadcast across inputs.
 685       nshape = [-1] + [1 for _ in range(inputs_rank - 1)]
 686       batch_weights = array_ops.reshape(batch_weights, nshape)
 687 
 688     if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW:
 689       moments_axes = [0] + list(range(2, inputs_rank))
 690       params_shape = inputs_shape[1:2]
 691       # For NCHW format, rather than relying on implicit broadcasting, we
 692       # explicitly reshape the params to params_shape_broadcast when computing
 693       # the moments and the batch normalization.
 694       params_shape_broadcast = list(
 695           [1, inputs_shape[1].value] + [1 for _ in range(2, inputs_rank)])
 696     else:
 697       moments_axes = list(range(inputs_rank - 1))
 698       params_shape = inputs_shape[-1:]
 699       params_shape_broadcast = None
 700     if not params_shape.is_fully_defined():
 701       raise ValueError('Inputs %s has undefined channels dimension %s.' %
 702                        (inputs.name, params_shape))
 703 
 704     # Allocate parameters for the beta and gamma of the normalization.
 705     beta, gamma = None, None
 706     if not param_initializers:
 707       param_initializers = {}
 708     if center:
 709       beta_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(variables_collections,
 710                                                         'beta')
 711       beta_initializer = param_initializers.get('beta',
 712                                                 init_ops.zeros_initializer())
 713       beta = variables.model_variable(
 714           'beta',
 715           shape=params_shape,
 716           dtype=dtype,
 717           initializer=beta_initializer,
 718           collections=beta_collections,
 719           trainable=trainable)
 720     if scale:
 721       gamma_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
 722           variables_collections, 'gamma')
 723       gamma_initializer = param_initializers.get('gamma',
 724                                                  init_ops.ones_initializer())
 725       gamma = variables.model_variable(
 726           'gamma',
 727           shape=params_shape,
 728           dtype=dtype,
 729           initializer=gamma_initializer,
 730           collections=gamma_collections,
 731           trainable=trainable)
 732 
 733     # Create moving_mean and moving_variance variables and add them to the
 734     # appropriate collections. We disable variable partitioning while creating
 735     # them, because assign_moving_average is not yet supported for partitioned
 736     # variables (this needs to be handled carefully, as it may break
 737     # the checkpoint backward compatibility).
 738     with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 739         variable_scope.get_variable_scope()) as local_scope:
 740       local_scope.set_partitioner(None)
 741       moving_mean_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
 742           variables_collections, 'moving_mean')
 743       moving_mean_initializer = param_initializers.get(
 744           'moving_mean', init_ops.zeros_initializer())
 745       moving_mean = variables.model_variable(
 746           'moving_mean',
 747           shape=params_shape,
 748           dtype=dtype,
 749           initializer=moving_mean_initializer,
 750           trainable=False,
 751           collections=moving_mean_collections)
 752       moving_variance_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
 753           variables_collections, 'moving_variance')
 754       moving_variance_initializer = param_initializers.get(
 755           'moving_variance', init_ops.ones_initializer())
 756       moving_variance = variables.model_variable(
 757           'moving_variance',
 758           shape=params_shape,
 759           dtype=dtype,
 760           initializer=moving_variance_initializer,
 761           trainable=False,
 762           collections=moving_variance_collections)
 763 
 764     # If `is_training` doesn't have a constant value, because it is a `Tensor`,
 765     # a `Variable` or `Placeholder` then is_training_value will be None and
 766     # `needs_moments` will be true.
 767     is_training_value = utils.constant_value(is_training)
 768     need_moments = is_training_value is None or is_training_value
 769     if need_moments:
 770       # Calculate the moments based on the individual batch.
 771       if batch_weights is None:
 772         if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW:
 773           mean, variance = nn.moments(inputs, moments_axes, keep_dims=True)
 774           mean = array_ops.reshape(mean, [-1])
 775           variance = array_ops.reshape(variance, [-1])
 776         else:
 777           mean, variance = nn.moments(inputs, moments_axes)
 778       else:
 779         if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW:
 780           mean, variance = nn.weighted_moments(
 781               inputs, moments_axes, batch_weights, keepdims=True)
 782           mean = array_ops.reshape(mean, [-1])
 783           variance = array_ops.reshape(variance, [-1])
 784         else:
 785           mean, variance = nn.weighted_moments(inputs, moments_axes,
 786                                                batch_weights)
 787 
 788       moving_vars_fn = lambda: (moving_mean, moving_variance)
 789       if updates_collections is None:
 790 
 791         def _force_updates():
 792           """Internal function forces updates moving_vars if is_training."""
 793           update_moving_mean = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 794               moving_mean, mean, decay, zero_debias=zero_debias_moving_mean)
 795           update_moving_variance = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 796               moving_variance, variance, decay, zero_debias=False)
 797           with ops.control_dependencies(
 798               [update_moving_mean, update_moving_variance]):
 799             return array_ops.identity(mean), array_ops.identity(variance)
 800 
 801         mean, variance = utils.smart_cond(is_training, _force_updates,
 802                                           moving_vars_fn)
 803       else:
 804 
 805         def _delay_updates():
 806           """Internal function that delay updates moving_vars if is_training."""
 807           update_moving_mean = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 808               moving_mean, mean, decay, zero_debias=zero_debias_moving_mean)
 809           update_moving_variance = moving_averages.assign_moving_average(
 810               moving_variance, variance, decay, zero_debias=False)
 811           return update_moving_mean, update_moving_variance
 812 
 813         update_mean, update_variance = utils.smart_cond(
 814             is_training, _delay_updates, moving_vars_fn)
 815         ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_mean)
 816         ops.add_to_collections(updates_collections, update_variance)
 817         # Use computed moments during training and moving_vars otherwise.
 818         vars_fn = lambda: (mean, variance)
 819         mean, variance = utils.smart_cond(is_training, vars_fn, moving_vars_fn)
 820     else:
 821       mean, variance = moving_mean, moving_variance
 822     if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW:
 823       mean = array_ops.reshape(mean, params_shape_broadcast)
 824       variance = array_ops.reshape(variance, params_shape_broadcast)
 825       if beta is not None:
 826         beta = array_ops.reshape(beta, params_shape_broadcast)
 827       if gamma is not None:
 828         gamma = array_ops.reshape(gamma, params_shape_broadcast)
 829 
 830     # Compute batch_normalization.
 831     outputs = nn.batch_normalization(inputs, mean, variance, beta, gamma,
 832                                      epsilon)
 833     outputs.set_shape(inputs_shape)
 834     if activation_fn is not None:
 835       outputs = activation_fn(outputs)
 836     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc.name, outputs)
 837 
 838 
 839 @add_arg_scope
 840 def bias_add(inputs,
 841              activation_fn=None,
 842              initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
 843              regularizer=None,
 844              reuse=None,
 845              variables_collections=None,
 846              outputs_collections=None,
 847              trainable=True,
 848              data_format=DATA_FORMAT_NHWC,
 849              scope=None):
 850   """Adds a bias to the inputs.
 851 
 852   Can be used as a normalizer function for conv2d and fully_connected.
 853 
 854   Args:
 855     inputs: A tensor of with at least rank 2 and value for the last dimension,
 856       e.g. `[batch_size, depth]`, `[None, None, None, depth]`.
 857     activation_fn: Activation function, default set to None to skip it and
 858       maintain a linear activation.
 859     initializer: An initializer for the bias, defaults to 0.
 860     regularizer: A regularizer like the result of
 861       `l1_regularizer` or `l2_regularizer`.
 862     reuse: Whether or not the layer and its variables should be reused. To be
 863       able to reuse the layer scope must be given.
 864     variables_collections: Optional collections for the variables.
 865     outputs_collections: Collections to add the outputs.
 866     trainable: If `True` also add variables to the graph collection
 867       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see tf.Variable).
 868     data_format: A string. 'NHWC' and 'NCHW' are supported.
 869     scope: Optional scope for variable_scope.
 870 
 871   Returns:
 872     A tensor representing the result of adding biases to the inputs.
 873 
 874   Raises:
 875     ValueError: If `data_format` is neither `NHWC` nor `NCHW`.
 876     ValueError: If `data_format` is `NCHW` and rank of `inputs` is not 4.
 877     ValueError: If the rank of `inputs` is undefined.
 878     ValueError: If rank or `C` dimension of `inputs` is undefined.
 879   """
 880   if data_format not in (DATA_FORMAT_NCHW, DATA_FORMAT_NHWC):
 881     raise ValueError('data_format has to be either NCHW or NHWC.')
 882   with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 883       scope, 'BiasAdd', [inputs], reuse=reuse) as sc:
 884     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
 885     dtype = inputs.dtype.base_dtype
 886     inputs_shape = inputs.get_shape()
 887     inputs_rank = inputs_shape.ndims
 888     if inputs_rank is None:
 889       raise ValueError('Dims of shape must be known but is None')
 890     elif inputs_rank != 4 and data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW:
 891       raise ValueError('Data format NCHW only supports 4D Tensor')
 892     axis = 1 if data_format == DATA_FORMAT_NCHW else -1
 893     num_features = inputs_shape[axis].value
 894     if num_features is None:
 895       raise ValueError('`C` dimension must be known but is None')
 896     biases_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(variables_collections,
 897                                                         'biases')
 898     biases = variables.model_variable(
 899         'biases',
 900         shape=[
 901             num_features,
 902         ],
 903         dtype=dtype,
 904         initializer=initializer,
 905         regularizer=regularizer,
 906         collections=biases_collections,
 907         trainable=trainable)
 908     outputs = nn.bias_add(inputs, biases, data_format=data_format)
 909     if activation_fn is not None:
 910       outputs = activation_fn(outputs)
 911     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc.name, outputs)
 912

 914 # TODO(jbms): change `rate` parameter to `dilation_rate` for consistency with
 915 # underlying op.
 916 @add_arg_scope
 917 def convolution(inputs,
 918                 num_outputs,
 919                 kernel_size,
 920                 stride=1,
 921                 padding='SAME',
 922                 data_format=None,
 923                 rate=1,
 924                 activation_fn=nn.relu,
 925                 normalizer_fn=None,
 926                 normalizer_params=None,
 927                 weights_initializer=initializers.xavier_initializer(),
 928                 weights_regularizer=None,
 929                 biases_initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
 930                 biases_regularizer=None,
 931                 reuse=None,
 932                 variables_collections=None,
 933                 outputs_collections=None,
 934                 trainable=True,
 935                 scope=None,
 936                 conv_dims=None):
 937   """Adds an N-D convolution followed by an optional batch_norm layer.
 938 
 939   It is required that 1 <= N <= 3.
 940 
 941   `convolution` creates a variable called `weights`, representing the
 942   convolutional kernel, that is convolved (actually cross-correlated) with the
 943   `inputs` to produce a `Tensor` of activations. If a `normalizer_fn` is
 944   provided (such as `batch_norm`), it is then applied. Otherwise, if
 945   `normalizer_fn` is None and a `biases_initializer` is provided then a `biases`
 946   variable would be created and added the activations. Finally, if
 947   `activation_fn` is not `None`, it is applied to the activations as well.
 948 
 949   Performs atrous convolution with input stride/dilation rate equal to `rate`
 950   if a value > 1 for any dimension of `rate` is specified.  In this case
 951   `stride` values != 1 are not supported.
 952 
 953   Args:
 954     inputs: A Tensor of rank N+2 of shape
 955       `[batch_size] + input_spatial_shape + [in_channels]` if data_format does
 956       not start with "NC" (default), or
 957       `[batch_size, in_channels] + input_spatial_shape` if data_format starts
 958       with "NC".
 959     num_outputs: Integer, the number of output filters.
 960     kernel_size: A sequence of N positive integers specifying the spatial
 961       dimensions of the filters.  Can be a single integer to specify the same
 962       value for all spatial dimensions.
 963     stride: A sequence of N positive integers specifying the stride at which to
 964       compute output.  Can be a single integer to specify the same value for all
 965       spatial dimensions.  Specifying any `stride` value != 1 is incompatible
 966       with specifying any `rate` value != 1.
 967     padding: One of `"VALID"` or `"SAME"`.
 968     data_format: A string or None.  Specifies whether the channel dimension of
 969       the `input` and output is the last dimension (default, or if `data_format`
 970       does not start with "NC"), or the second dimension (if `data_format`
 971       starts with "NC").  For N=1, the valid values are "NWC" (default) and
 972       "NCW".  For N=2, the valid values are "NHWC" (default) and "NCHW".
 973       For N=3, the valid values are "NDHWC" (default) and "NCDHW".
 974     rate: A sequence of N positive integers specifying the dilation rate to use
 975       for atrous convolution.  Can be a single integer to specify the same
 976       value for all spatial dimensions.  Specifying any `rate` value != 1 is
 977       incompatible with specifying any `stride` value != 1.
 978     activation_fn: Activation function. The default value is a ReLU function.
 979       Explicitly set it to None to skip it and maintain a linear activation.
 980     normalizer_fn: Normalization function to use instead of `biases`. If
 981       `normalizer_fn` is provided then `biases_initializer` and
 982       `biases_regularizer` are ignored and `biases` are not created nor added.
 983       default set to None for no normalizer function
 984     normalizer_params: Normalization function parameters.
 985     weights_initializer: An initializer for the weights.
 986     weights_regularizer: Optional regularizer for the weights.
 987     biases_initializer: An initializer for the biases. If None skip biases.
 988     biases_regularizer: Optional regularizer for the biases.
 989     reuse: Whether or not the layer and its variables should be reused. To be
 990       able to reuse the layer scope must be given.
 991     variables_collections: Optional list of collections for all the variables or
 992       a dictionary containing a different list of collection per variable.
 993     outputs_collections: Collection to add the outputs.
 994     trainable: If `True` also add variables to the graph collection
 995       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see tf.Variable).
 996     scope: Optional scope for `variable_scope`.
 997     conv_dims: Optional convolution dimensionality, when set it would use the
 998       corresponding convolution (e.g. 2 for Conv 2D, 3 for Conv 3D, ..). When
 999       leaved to None it would select the convolution dimensionality based on
1000       the input rank (i.e. Conv ND, with N = input_rank - 2).
1001 
1002   Returns:
1003     A tensor representing the output of the operation.
1004 
1005   Raises:
1006     ValueError: If `data_format` is invalid.
1007     ValueError: Both 'rate' and `stride` are not uniformly 1.
1008   """
1009   if data_format not in [None, 'NWC', 'NCW', 'NHWC', 'NCHW', 'NDHWC', 'NCDHW']:
1010     raise ValueError('Invalid data_format: %r' % (data_format,))
1011 
1012   layer_variable_getter = _build_variable_getter({
1013       'bias': 'biases',
1014       'kernel': 'weights'
1015   })
1016 
1017   with variable_scope.variable_scope(
1018       scope, 'Conv', [inputs], reuse=reuse,
1019       custom_getter=layer_variable_getter) as sc:
1020     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
1021     input_rank = inputs.get_shape().ndims
1022 
1023     if conv_dims is not None and conv_dims + 2 != input_rank:
1024       raise ValueError('Convolution expects input with rank %d, got %d' %
1025                        (conv_dims + 2, input_rank))
1026     if input_rank == 3:
1027       layer_class = convolutional_layers.Convolution1D
1028     elif input_rank == 4:
1029       layer_class = convolutional_layers.Convolution2D
1030     elif input_rank == 5:
1031       layer_class = convolutional_layers.Convolution3D
1032     else:
1033       raise ValueError('Convolution not supported for input with rank',
1034                        input_rank)
1035 
1036     df = ('channels_first'
1037           if data_format and data_format.startswith('NC') else 'channels_last')
1038     layer = layer_class(
1039         filters=num_outputs,
1040         kernel_size=kernel_size,
1041         strides=stride,
1042         padding=padding,
1043         data_format=df,

1201 @add_arg_scope
1202 def convolution2d_in_plane(
1203     inputs,
1204     kernel_size,
1205     stride=1,
1206     padding='SAME',
1207     activation_fn=nn.relu,
1208     normalizer_fn=None,
1209     normalizer_params=None,
1210     weights_initializer=initializers.xavier_initializer(),
1211     weights_regularizer=None,
1212     biases_initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
1213     biases_regularizer=None,
1214     reuse=None,
1215     variables_collections=None,
1216     outputs_collections=None,
1217     trainable=True,
1218     scope=None):
1219   """Performs the same in-plane convolution to each channel independently.
1220 
1221   This is useful for performing various simple channel-independent convolution
1222   operations such as image gradients:
1223 
1224     image = tf.constant(..., shape=(16, 240, 320, 3))
1225     vert_gradients = layers.conv2d_in_plane(image,
1226                                             kernel=[1, -1],
1227                                             kernel_size=[2, 1])
1228     horz_gradients = layers.conv2d_in_plane(image,
1229                                             kernel=[1, -1],
1230                                             kernel_size=[1, 2])
1231 
1232   Args:
1233     inputs: A 4-D tensor with dimensions [batch_size, height, width, channels].
1234     kernel_size: A list of length 2 holding the [kernel_height, kernel_width] of
1235       of the pooling. Can be an int if both values are the same.
1236     stride: A list of length 2 `[stride_height, stride_width]`.
1237       Can be an int if both strides are the same. Note that presently
1238       both strides must have the same value.
1239     padding: The padding type to use, either 'SAME' or 'VALID'.
1240     activation_fn: Activation function. The default value is a ReLU function.
1241       Explicitly set it to None to skip it and maintain a linear activation.
1242     normalizer_fn: Normalization function to use instead of `biases`. If
1243       `normalizer_fn` is provided then `biases_initializer` and
1244       `biases_regularizer` are ignored and `biases` are not created nor added.
1245       default set to None for no normalizer function
1246     normalizer_params: Normalization function parameters.
1247     weights_initializer: An initializer for the weights.
1248     weights_regularizer: Optional regularizer for the weights.
1249     biases_initializer: An initializer for the biases. If None skip biases.
1250     biases_regularizer: Optional regularizer for the biases.
1251     reuse: Whether or not the layer and its variables should be reused. To be
1252       able to reuse the layer scope must be given.
1253     variables_collections: Optional list of collections for all the variables or
1254       a dictionary containing a different list of collection per variable.
1255     outputs_collections: Collection to add the outputs.
1256     trainable: If `True` also add variables to the graph collection
1257       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see tf.Variable).
1258     scope: Optional scope for `variable_scope`.
1259 
1260   Returns:
1261     A `Tensor` representing the output of the operation.
1262   """
1263   with variable_scope.variable_scope(
1264       scope, 'ConvInPlane', [inputs], reuse=reuse) as sc:
1265     dtype = inputs.dtype.base_dtype
1266     kernel_h, kernel_w = utils.two_element_tuple(kernel_size)
1267     stride_h, stride_w = utils.two_element_tuple(stride)
1268     num_filters_in = utils.last_dimension(inputs.get_shape(), min_rank=4)
1269     weights_shape = [kernel_h, kernel_w, 1, 1]
1270     weights_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
1271         variables_collections, 'weights')
1272     weights = variables.model_variable(
1273         'weights',
1274         shape=weights_shape,
1275         dtype=dtype,
1276         initializer=weights_initializer,
1277         regularizer=weights_regularizer,
1278         collections=weights_collections,
1279         trainable=trainable)
1280     depthwise_weights = array_ops.tile(weights, [1, 1, num_filters_in, 1])
1281     outputs = nn.depthwise_conv2d(inputs, depthwise_weights,
1282                                   [1, stride_h, stride_w, 1], padding)
1283     if normalizer_fn is not None:
1284       normalizer_params = normalizer_params or {}
1285       outputs = normalizer_fn(outputs, **normalizer_params)
1286     else:
1287       if biases_initializer is not None:
1288         biases_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
1289             variables_collections, 'biases')
1290         biases = variables.model_variable(
1291             'biases',
1292             shape=[
1293                 num_filters_in,
1294             ],
1295             dtype=dtype,
1296             initializer=biases_initializer,
1297             regularizer=biases_regularizer,
1298             collections=biases_collections,
1299             trainable=trainable)
1300         outputs = nn.bias_add(outputs, biases)
1301 
1302     if activation_fn is not None:
1303       outputs = activation_fn(outputs)
1304     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc.name, outputs)

1538   """Converts a dense tensor into a sparse tensor.
1539 
1540   An example use would be to convert dense labels to sparse ones
1541   so that they can be fed to the ctc_loss.

1561 @add_arg_scope

1563             keep_prob=0.5,

1627 def _sparse_inner_flatten(inputs, new_rank):
1628   """Helper function for `inner_flatten`."""
1629   inputs_rank = inputs.dense_shape.get_shape().as_list()[0]
1630   if inputs_rank < new_rank:
1631     raise ValueError(
1632         'Inputs has rank less than new_rank. {} must have rank at least'
1633         ' {}. Received rank {}, shape {}'.format(inputs, new_rank, inputs_rank,
1634                                                  inputs.get_shape()))
1635 
1636   outer_dimensions = inputs.dense_shape[:new_rank - 1]
1637   inner_dimensions = inputs.dense_shape[new_rank - 1:]
1638   new_shape = array_ops.concat(
1639       (outer_dimensions, [math_ops.reduce_prod(inner_dimensions)]), 0)
1640   flattened = sparse_ops.sparse_reshape(inputs, new_shape)
1641   return flattened
1642 
1643 
1644 def _dense_inner_flatten(inputs, new_rank):
1645   """Helper function for `inner_flatten`."""
1646   rank_assertion = check_ops.assert_rank_at_least(
1647       inputs, new_rank, message='inputs has rank less than new_rank')
1648   with ops.control_dependencies([rank_assertion]):
1649     outer_dimensions = array_ops.strided_slice(
1650         array_ops.shape(inputs), [0], [new_rank - 1])
1651     new_shape = array_ops.concat((outer_dimensions, [-1]), 0)
1652     reshaped = array_ops.reshape(inputs, new_shape)
1653 
1654   # if `new_rank` is an integer, try to calculate new shape.
1655   if isinstance(new_rank, six.integer_types):
1656     static_shape = inputs.get_shape()
1657     if static_shape is not None and static_shape.dims is not None:
1658       static_shape = static_shape.as_list()
1659       static_outer_dims = static_shape[:new_rank - 1]
1660       static_inner_dims = static_shape[new_rank - 1:]
1661       flattened_dimension = 1
1662       for inner_dim in static_inner_dims:
1663         if inner_dim is None:
1664           flattened_dimension = None
1665           break
1666         flattened_dimension *= inner_dim
1667       reshaped.set_shape(static_outer_dims + [flattened_dimension])
1668   return reshaped
1669 
1670 
1671 @add_arg_scope
1672 def _inner_flatten(inputs, new_rank, output_collections=None, scope=None):
1673   """Flattens inner dimensions of `inputs`, returns a Tensor with `new_rank`.
1674 
1675   For example:
1676   '''
1677       x = tf.random_uniform(shape=[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6])
1678       y = _inner_flatten(x, 4)
1679       assert y.get_shape().as_list() == [1, 2, 3, (4 * 5 * 6)]
1680   '''
1681   This layer will fail at run time if `new_rank` is greater than the current
1682   rank of `inputs`.
1683 
1684   Args:
1685     inputs: A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor`.
1686     new_rank: The desired rank of the returned `Tensor` or `SparseTensor`.
1687     output_collections: Collection to which the outputs will be added.
1688     scope: Optional scope for `name_scope`.
1689   Returns:
1690     A `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` containing the same values as `inputs`, but
1691     with innermost dimensions flattened to obtain rank `new_rank`.
1692 
1693   Raises:
1694     TypeError: `inputs` is not a `Tensor` or `SparseTensor`.
1695   """
1696   with ops.name_scope(scope, 'InnerFlatten', [inputs, new_rank]) as sc:
1697     if isinstance(inputs, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
1698       flattened = _sparse_inner_flatten(inputs, new_rank)
1699     else:
1700       inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
1701       flattened = _dense_inner_flatten(inputs, new_rank)
1702   return utils.collect_named_outputs(output_collections, sc, flattened)

1754 def _add_variable_to_collections(variable, collections_set, collections_name):
1755   """Adds variable (or all its parts) to all collections with that name."""
1756   collections = utils.get_variable_collections(collections_set,
1757                                                collections_name) or []

1760     variables_list = [v for v in variable]

1767 @add_arg_scope
1768 def fully_connected(inputs,
1769                     num_outputs,
1770                     activation_fn=nn.relu,
1771                     normalizer_fn=None,
1772                     normalizer_params=None,
1773                     weights_initializer=initializers.xavier_initializer(),
1774                     weights_regularizer=None,
1775                     biases_initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
1776                     biases_regularizer=None,
1777                     reuse=None,
1778                     variables_collections=None,
1779                     outputs_collections=None,
1780                     trainable=True,
1781                     scope=None):
1782   """Adds a fully connected layer.
1783 
1784   `fully_connected` creates a variable called `weights`, representing a fully
1785   connected weight matrix, which is multiplied by the `inputs` to produce a
1786   `Tensor` of hidden units. If a `normalizer_fn` is provided (such as
1787   `batch_norm`), it is then applied. Otherwise, if `normalizer_fn` is
1788   None and a `biases_initializer` is provided then a `biases` variable would be
1789   created and added the hidden units. Finally, if `activation_fn` is not `None`,
1790   it is applied to the hidden units as well.
1791 
1792   Note: that if `inputs` have a rank greater than 2, then `inputs` is flattened
1793   prior to the initial matrix multiply by `weights`.
1794 
1795   Args:
1796     inputs: A tensor of at least rank 2 and static value for the last dimension;
1797       i.e. `[batch_size, depth]`, `[None, None, None, channels]`.
1798     num_outputs: Integer or long, the number of output units in the layer.
1799     activation_fn: Activation function. The default value is a ReLU function.
1800       Explicitly set it to None to skip it and maintain a linear activation.
1801     normalizer_fn: Normalization function to use instead of `biases`. If
1802       `normalizer_fn` is provided then `biases_initializer` and
1803       `biases_regularizer` are ignored and `biases` are not created nor added.
1804       default set to None for no normalizer function
1805     normalizer_params: Normalization function parameters.
1806     weights_initializer: An initializer for the weights.
1807     weights_regularizer: Optional regularizer for the weights.
1808     biases_initializer: An initializer for the biases. If None skip biases.
1809     biases_regularizer: Optional regularizer for the biases.
1810     reuse: Whether or not the layer and its variables should be reused. To be
1811       able to reuse the layer scope must be given.
1812     variables_collections: Optional list of collections for all the variables or
1813       a dictionary containing a different list of collections per variable.
1814     outputs_collections: Collection to add the outputs.
1815     trainable: If `True` also add variables to the graph collection
1816       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see tf.Variable).
1817     scope: Optional scope for variable_scope.
1818 
1819   Returns:
1820      The tensor variable representing the result of the series of operations.
1821 
1822   Raises:
1823     ValueError: If x has rank less than 2 or if its last dimension is not set.
1824   """
1825   if not isinstance(num_outputs, six.integer_types):
1826     raise ValueError('num_outputs should be int or long, got %s.' %
1827                      (num_outputs,))
1828 
1829   layer_variable_getter = _build_variable_getter({
1830       'bias': 'biases',
1831       'kernel': 'weights'
1832   })
1833 
1834   with variable_scope.variable_scope(
1835       scope,
1836       'fully_connected', [inputs],
1837       reuse=reuse,
1838       custom_getter=layer_variable_getter) as sc:
1839     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
1840     layer = core_layers.Dense(
1841         units=num_outputs,
1842         activation=None,
1843         use_bias=not normalizer_fn and biases_initializer,
1844         kernel_initializer=weights_initializer,
1845         bias_initializer=biases_initializer,
1846         kernel_regularizer=weights_regularizer,
1847         bias_regularizer=biases_regularizer,
1848         activity_regularizer=None,
1849         trainable=trainable,
1850         name=sc.name,
1851         dtype=inputs.dtype.base_dtype,
1852         _scope=sc,
1853         _reuse=reuse)
1854     outputs = layer.apply(inputs)
1855 
1856     # Add variables to collections.
1857     _add_variable_to_collections(layer.kernel, variables_collections, 'weights')
1858     if layer.bias is not None:
1859       _add_variable_to_collections(layer.bias, variables_collections, 'biases')
1860 
1861     # Apply normalizer function / layer.
1862     if normalizer_fn is not None:
1863       if not normalizer_params:
1864         normalizer_params = {}
1865       outputs = normalizer_fn(outputs, **normalizer_params)
1866 
1867     if activation_fn is not None:
1868       outputs = activation_fn(outputs)
1869 
1870     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc.name, outputs)
1871 
1872 
1873 class GDN(base.Layer):
1874   """Generalized divisive normalization layer.
1875 
1876   Based on the papers:
1877 
1878     "Density Modeling of Images using a Generalized Normalization
1879     Transformation"
1880 
1881     Johannes Ballé, Valero Laparra, Eero P. Simoncelli
1882 
1883     https://arxiv.org/abs/1511.06281
1884 
1885     "End-to-end Optimized Image Compression"
1886 
1887     Johannes Ballé, Valero Laparra, Eero P. Simoncelli
1888 
1889     https://arxiv.org/abs/1611.01704
1890 
1891   Implements an activation function that is essentially a multivariate
1892   generalization of a particular sigmoid-type function:
1893 
1894   ```
1895   y[i] = x[i] / sqrt(beta[i] + sum_j(gamma[j, i] * x[j]))
1896   ```
1897 
1898   where `i` and `j` run over channels. This implementation never sums across
1899   spatial dimensions. It is similar to local response normalization, but much
1900   more flexible, as `beta` and `gamma` are trainable parameters.
1901 
1902   Arguments:
1903     inverse: If `False` (default), compute GDN response. If `True`, compute IGDN
1904       response (one step of fixed point iteration to invert GDN; the division
1905       is replaced by multiplication).
1906     beta_min: Lower bound for beta, to prevent numerical error from causing
1907       square root of zero or negative values.
1908     gamma_init: The gamma matrix will be initialized as the identity matrix
1909       multiplied with this value. If set to zero, the layer is effectively
1910       initialized to the identity operation, since beta is initialized as one.
1911       A good default setting is somewhere between 0 and 0.5.
1912     reparam_offset: Offset added to the reparameterization of beta and gamma.
1913       The reparameterization of beta and gamma as their square roots lets the
1914       training slow down when their values are close to zero, which is desirable
1915       as small values in the denominator can lead to a situation where gradient
1916       noise on beta/gamma leads to extreme amounts of noise in the GDN
1917       activations. However, without the offset, we would get zero gradients if
1918       any elements of beta or gamma were exactly zero, and thus the training
1919       could get stuck. To prevent this, we add this small constant. The default
1920       value was empirically determined as a good starting point. Making it
1921       bigger potentially leads to more gradient noise on the activations, making
1922       it too small may lead to numerical precision issues.
1923     data_format: Format of input tensor. Currently supports `'channels_first'`
1924       and `'channels_last'`.
1925     activity_regularizer: Regularizer function for the output.
1926     trainable: Boolean, if `True`, also add variables to the graph collection
1927       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see `tf.Variable`).
1928     name: String, the name of the layer. Layers with the same name will
1929       share weights, but to avoid mistakes we require `reuse=True` in such
1930       cases.
1931 
1932   Properties:
1933     inverse: Boolean, whether GDN is computed (`True`) or IGDN (`False`).
1934     data_format: Format of input tensor. Currently supports `'channels_first'`
1935       and `'channels_last'`.
1936     beta: The beta parameter as defined above (1D `Tensor`).
1937     gamma: The gamma parameter as defined above (2D `Tensor`).
1938   """
1939 
1940   def __init__(self,
1941                inverse=False,
1942                beta_min=1e-6,
1943                gamma_init=.1,
1944                reparam_offset=2**-18,
1945                data_format='channels_last',
1946                activity_regularizer=None,
1947                trainable=True,
1948                name=None,
1949                **kwargs):
1950     super(GDN, self).__init__(
1951         trainable=trainable,
1952         name=name,
1953         activity_regularizer=activity_regularizer,
1954         **kwargs)
1955     self.inverse = inverse
1956     self._beta_min = beta_min
1957     self._gamma_init = gamma_init
1958     self._reparam_offset = reparam_offset
1959     self.data_format = data_format
1960     self._channel_axis()  # trigger ValueError early
1961     self.input_spec = base.InputSpec(min_ndim=3, max_ndim=5)
1962 
1963   def _channel_axis(self):
1964     try:
1965       return {'channels_first': 1, 'channels_last': -1}[self.data_format]
1966     except KeyError:
1967       raise ValueError('Unsupported `data_format` for GDN layer: {}.'.format(
1968           self.data_format))
1969 
1970   @staticmethod
1971   def _lower_bound(inputs, bound, name=None):
1972     """Same as tf.maximum, but with helpful gradient for inputs < bound.
1973 
1974     The gradient is overwritten so that it is passed through if the input is not
1975     hitting the bound. If it is, only gradients that push `inputs` higher than
1976     the bound are passed through. No gradients are passed through to the bound.
1977 
1978     Args:
1979       inputs: input tensor
1980       bound: lower bound for the input tensor
1981       name: name for this op
1982 
1983     Returns:
1984       tf.maximum(inputs, bound)
1985     """
1986     with ops.name_scope(name, 'GDNLowerBound', [inputs, bound]) as scope:
1987       inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs, name='inputs')
1988       bound = ops.convert_to_tensor(bound, name='bound')
1989       with ops.get_default_graph().gradient_override_map({
1990           'Maximum': 'GDNLowerBound'
1991       }):
1992         return math_ops.maximum(inputs, bound, name=scope)
1993 
1994   @staticmethod
1995   def _lower_bound_grad(op, grad):
1996     """Gradient for `_lower_bound`.
1997 
1998     Args:
1999       op: the tensorflow op for which to calculate a gradient
2000       grad: gradient with respect to the output of the op
2001 
2002     Returns:
2003       gradients with respect to the inputs of the op
2004     """
2005     inputs = op.inputs[0]
2006     bound = op.inputs[1]
2007     pass_through_if = math_ops.logical_or(inputs >= bound, grad < 0)
2008     return [math_ops.cast(pass_through_if, grad.dtype) * grad, None]
2009 
2010   def build(self, input_shape):
2011     channel_axis = self._channel_axis()
2012     input_shape = tensor_shape.TensorShape(input_shape)
2013     num_channels = input_shape[channel_axis].value
2014     if num_channels is None:
2015       raise ValueError('The channel dimension of the inputs to `GDN` '
2016                        'must be defined.')
2017     self._input_rank = input_shape.ndims
2018     self.input_spec = base.InputSpec(
2019         ndim=input_shape.ndims, axes={
2020             channel_axis: num_channels
2021         })
2022 
2023     pedestal = array_ops.constant(self._reparam_offset**2, dtype=self.dtype)
2024     beta_bound = array_ops.constant(
2025         (self._beta_min + self._reparam_offset**2)**.5, dtype=self.dtype)
2026     gamma_bound = array_ops.constant(self._reparam_offset, dtype=self.dtype)
2027 
2028     def beta_initializer(shape, dtype=None, partition_info=None):
2029       del partition_info  # unused
2030       pedestal = array_ops.constant(self._reparam_offset**2, dtype=self.dtype)
2031       return math_ops.sqrt(array_ops.ones(shape, dtype=dtype) + pedestal)
2032 
2033     def gamma_initializer(shape, dtype=None, partition_info=None):
2034       del partition_info  # unused
2035       assert len(shape) == 2
2036       assert shape[0] == shape[1]
2037       eye = linalg_ops.eye(shape[0], dtype=dtype)
2038       pedestal = array_ops.constant(self._reparam_offset**2, dtype=self.dtype)
2039       return math_ops.sqrt(self._gamma_init * eye + pedestal)
2040 
2041     beta = self.add_variable(
2042         'reparam_beta',
2043         shape=[num_channels],
2044         initializer=beta_initializer,
2045         dtype=self.dtype,
2046         trainable=True)
2047     beta = self._lower_bound(beta, beta_bound)
2048     self.beta = math_ops.square(beta) - pedestal
2049 
2050     gamma = self.add_variable(
2051         'reparam_gamma',
2052         shape=[num_channels, num_channels],
2053         initializer=gamma_initializer,
2054         dtype=self.dtype,
2055         trainable=True)
2056     gamma = self._lower_bound(gamma, gamma_bound)
2057     self.gamma = math_ops.square(gamma) - pedestal
2058 
2059     self.built = True
2060 
2061   def call(self, inputs):
2062     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs, dtype=self.dtype)
2063     ndim = self._input_rank
2064 
2065     shape = self.gamma.get_shape().as_list()
2066     gamma = array_ops.reshape(self.gamma, (ndim - 2) * [1] + shape)
2067 
2068     # Compute normalization pool.
2069     if self.data_format == 'channels_first':
2070       norm_pool = nn.convolution(
2071           math_ops.square(inputs),
2072           gamma,
2073           'VALID',
2074           data_format='NC' + 'DHW' [-(ndim - 2):])
2075       if ndim == 3:
2076         norm_pool = array_ops.expand_dims(norm_pool, 2)
2077         norm_pool = nn.bias_add(norm_pool, self.beta, data_format='NCHW')
2078         norm_pool = array_ops.squeeze(norm_pool, [2])
2079       elif ndim == 5:
2080         shape = array_ops.shape(norm_pool)
2081         norm_pool = array_ops.reshape(norm_pool, shape[:3] + [-1])
2082         norm_pool = nn.bias_add(norm_pool, self.beta, data_format='NCHW')
2083         norm_pool = array_ops.reshape(norm_pool, shape)
2084       else:  # ndim == 4
2085         norm_pool = nn.bias_add(norm_pool, self.beta, data_format='NCHW')
2086     else:  # channels_last
2087       norm_pool = nn.convolution(math_ops.square(inputs), gamma, 'VALID')
2088       norm_pool = nn.bias_add(norm_pool, self.beta, data_format='NHWC')
2089     norm_pool = math_ops.sqrt(norm_pool)
2090 
2091     if self.inverse:
2092       outputs = inputs * norm_pool
2093     else:
2094       outputs = inputs / norm_pool
2095     outputs.set_shape(inputs.get_shape())
2096     return outputs
2097 
2098   def compute_output_shape(self, input_shape):
2099     channel_axis = self._channel_axis()
2100     input_shape = tensor_shape.TensorShape(input_shape)
2101     if not 3 <= input_shape.ndim <= 5:
2102       raise ValueError('`input_shape` must be of rank 3 to 5, inclusive.')
2103     if input_shape[channel_axis].value is None:
2104       raise ValueError(
2105           'The channel dimension of `input_shape` must be defined.')
2106     return input_shape

2213     "Layer Normalization"
2214 
2215     Jimmy Lei Ba, Jamie Ryan Kiros, Geoffrey E. Hinton
2216 
2217     https://arxiv.org/abs/1607.06450.
2218 
2219   Can be used as a normalizer function for conv2d and fully_connected.
2220 
2221   Given a tensor `inputs` of rank `R`, moments are calculated and normalization
2222   is performed over axes `begin_norm_axis ... R - 1`.  Scaling and centering,
2223   if requested, is performed over axes `begin_params_axis .. R - 1`.
2224 
2225   By default, `begin_norm_axis = 1` and `begin_params_axis = -1`,
2226   meaning that normalization is performed over all but the first axis
2227   (the `HWC` if `inputs` is `NHWC`), while the `beta` and `gamma` trainable
2228   parameters are calculated for the rightmost axis (the `C` if `inputs` is
2229   `NHWC`).  Scaling and recentering is performed via broadcast of the
2230   `beta` and `gamma` parameters with the normalized tensor.
2231 
2232   The shapes of `beta` and `gamma` are `inputs.shape[begin_params_axis:]`,
2233   and this part of the inputs' shape must be fully defined.
2234 
2235   Args:
2236     inputs: A tensor having rank `R`. The normalization is performed over
2237       axes `begin_norm_axis ... R - 1` and centering and scaling parameters
2238       are calculated over `begin_params_axis ... R - 1`.
2239     center: If True, add offset of `beta` to normalized tensor. If False, `beta`
2240       is ignored.
2241     scale: If True, multiply by `gamma`. If False, `gamma` is
2242       not used. When the next layer is linear (also e.g. `nn.relu`), this can be
2243       disabled since the scaling can be done by the next layer.
2244     activation_fn: Activation function, default set to None to skip it and
2245       maintain a linear activation.
2246     reuse: Whether or not the layer and its variables should be reused. To be
2247       able to reuse the layer scope must be given.
2248     variables_collections: Optional collections for the variables.
2249     outputs_collections: Collections to add the outputs.
2250     trainable: If `True` also add variables to the graph collection
2251       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see tf.Variable).
2252     begin_norm_axis: The first normalization dimension: normalization will be
2253       performed along dimensions `begin_norm_axis : rank(inputs)`
2254     begin_params_axis: The first parameter (beta, gamma) dimension: scale
2255       and centering parameters will have dimensions
2256       `begin_params_axis : rank(inputs)` and will be broadcast with the
2257       normalized inputs accordingly.
2258     scope: Optional scope for `variable_scope`.
2259 
2260   Returns:
2261     A `Tensor` representing the output of the operation, having the same
2262     shape and dtype as `inputs`.
2263 
2264   Raises:
2265     ValueError: If the rank of `inputs` is not known at graph build time,
2266       or if `inputs.shape[begin_params_axis:]` is not fully defined at
2267       graph build time.
2268   """
2269   with variable_scope.variable_scope(
2270       scope, 'LayerNorm', [inputs], reuse=reuse) as sc:
2271     inputs = ops.convert_to_tensor(inputs)
2272     inputs_shape = inputs.shape
2273     inputs_rank = inputs_shape.ndims
2274     if inputs_rank is None:
2275       raise ValueError('Inputs %s has undefined rank.' % inputs.name)
2276     dtype = inputs.dtype.base_dtype
2277     if begin_norm_axis < 0:
2278       begin_norm_axis = inputs_rank + begin_norm_axis
2279     if begin_params_axis >= inputs_rank or begin_norm_axis >= inputs_rank:
2280       raise ValueError('begin_params_axis (%d) and begin_norm_axis (%d) '
2281                        'must be < rank(inputs) (%d)' %
2282                        (begin_params_axis, begin_norm_axis, inputs_rank))
2283     params_shape = inputs_shape[begin_params_axis:]
2284     if not params_shape.is_fully_defined():
2285       raise ValueError(
2286           'Inputs %s: shape(inputs)[%s:] is not fully defined: %s' %
2287           (inputs.name, begin_params_axis, inputs_shape))
2288     # Allocate parameters for the beta and gamma of the normalization.
2289     beta, gamma = None, None
2290     if center:
2291       beta_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(variables_collections,
2292                                                         'beta')
2293       beta = variables.model_variable(
2294           'beta',
2295           shape=params_shape,
2296           dtype=dtype,
2297           initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
2298           collections=beta_collections,
2299           trainable=trainable)
2300     if scale:
2301       gamma_collections = utils.get_variable_collections(
2302           variables_collections, 'gamma')
2303       gamma = variables.model_variable(
2304           'gamma',
2305           shape=params_shape,
2306           dtype=dtype,
2307           initializer=init_ops.ones_initializer(),
2308           collections=gamma_collections,
2309           trainable=trainable)
2310     # Calculate the moments on the last axis (layer activations).
2311     norm_axes = list(range(begin_norm_axis, inputs_rank))
2312     mean, variance = nn.moments(inputs, norm_axes, keep_dims=True)
2313     # Compute layer normalization using the batch_normalization function.
2314     variance_epsilon = 1e-12
2315     outputs = nn.batch_normalization(
2316         inputs,
2317         mean,
2318         variance,
2319         offset=beta,
2320         scale=gamma,
2321         variance_epsilon=variance_epsilon)
2322     outputs.set_shape(inputs_shape)
2323     if activation_fn is not None:
2324       outputs = activation_fn(outputs)
2325     return utils.collect_named_outputs(outputs_collections, sc.name, outputs)
